{{Quote|They served the god Kad Ha'rangir, whose tests and trials forced change and growth upon the clans he chose to be his people.|[[Vilnau Teupt]], speaking about the [[Mandalorian Crusaders]]|<ref name="TEGW">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref>}}
'''Kad Ha'rangir''' was a [[Deity/Legends|deity]] in the ancient [[Mandalorian religion]]. Known as the destroyer god, the vigorous Kad Ha'rangir was viewed by the [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorians]] as the bringer of change and growth upon the [[Universe/Legends|universe]]. Kad Ha'rangir opposed the sloth-god [[Arasuum]]—the personification of idleness and stagnation—in a war that spanned eternity.<ref name="TMPaC" />

The ancient Mandalorians waged ritual warfare<ref name="HotM">{{InsiderCite|80|The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors}}</ref> as a means of worship to Kad Ha'rangir, seeking his favor as they defied the temptations of idle consumption offered by Arasuum.<ref name="TEGW" /> These [[Soldier/Legends|warriors]] became known as [[Mandalorian Crusaders]], a reflection of the holiness embodied by the conflict they engaged in,<ref name="HotM" /> and viewed their clans as Kad Ha'rangir's chosen people.<ref name="TEGW" />

Over [[Time/Legends|time]], worship of Kad Ha'rangir and the belief in Arasuum fell out of favor in the Mandalorian culture. Upon witnessing a spiritual vision on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Shogun (planet)|Shogun]], the Mandalorian [[Mandalore (title)/Legends|leader]] known as [[Mandalore the Indomitable]] preached that the act of war itself would be the center of Mandalorian worship, and that to wage war was to be divine,<ref name="TEGW" /> though the worship of war, too, would decline as the [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] passed.<ref name="TMPaC" />

However, Kad Ha'rangir and the Mandalorian gods were not completely forgotten. For instance, [[Clan Ha'rangir]] of the [[Hidden Chain]] claimed to have been descended from the god.<ref name="Legacy of the Sith">''[[Star Wars: The Old Republic: Legacy of the Sith]]''</ref> Additionally, millennia later, in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]], the Mandalorian soldier [[Kal Skirata]] knew of their former place in Mandalorian mythology,<ref name="O66">''[[Order 66: A Republic Commando Novel]]''</ref> and the [[Historian/Legends|historian]] [[Vilnau Teupt]] recounted their importance to the early Mandalorians during his [[Industry, Honor, Savagery: Shaping the Mandalorian Soul|keynote speech]] at the four hundred twelfth [[Proceedings of Galactic Anthropology and History]] at the [[Brentaal Academy]] in [[24 ABY/Legends|24 ABY]].<ref name="TEGW" />

==Behind the scenes==
Kad Ha'rangir first appeared in ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] in the article titled ''[[The Mandalorians: People and Culture]]''. [[Author/Legends|Authored]] by [[Karen Traviss]], the article was published [[February]] [[2006]] as part of the [[Star Wars Insider 86|eighty-sixth issue]] of the ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'' magazine. Kad Ha'rangir was also mentioned in the later reference book ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'', written by [[Jason Fry]] and [[Paul R. Urquhart]], and published [[April 3]], [[2012]].

